headline: The Dow Industrials Have Tilted More Toward Financials
summary: Since the Dow hit 40000 for the first time nearly two years ago, the index has grown heavier in financial stocks and trimmed back its exposure to the health-care sector.  Much of this is due to the recent outperformance of financial stocks like Goldman Sachs and JPMorgan, and the relative underperformance of stocks like Merck and UnitedHealth.  Two new stocks have come into the index—Nvidia and Sherwin-Williams—during the Dow’s "40-something" years.

headline: Dow Crosses 50,000 Level
summary: The Dow Jones Industrial Average crossed 50,000 for the first time on Friday.  The Nasdaq Composite rallied 1.9%.  The majority of stocks in the index were rallying on Friday, but the Dow got a big boost from Nvidia, Caterpillar, and Goldman Sachs.

headline: S&P 500 Health Insurer Dives As ACA Enrollment Implodes
summary: S&P 500 health insurer Molina Healthcare crashed to a nearly six-year low on Friday morning after posting an unexpected loss amid surging health benefit costs.  Centene, another S&P 500 member, also reported a loss, though that was anticipated.  Molina said that it expects insured Affordable Care Act Marketplace membership to sink from 713,000 at the end of Q3 to just 220,000 at the end of 2026.

headline: UnitedHealth Group (UNH) Valuation Check After Steep Recent Share Price Pullback
summary: Why UnitedHealth Group Is Drawing Attention Now UnitedHealth Group (UNH) is on many investors’ radar after a period of negative share performance, including a 23% decline over the past month and a 17% decline over the past 3 months. This recent pullback contrasts with the company’s scale, with reported revenue of US$447.6b and net income of US$12.1b. headline: Molina Healthcare Stock Falls 27%. Why Its Earnings Outlook Is So Bleak.
summary: Molina Healthcare stock tanked ahead of the open Friday after the insurer issued a disappointing earnings outlook for 2026.  Amid broad concerns across the healthcare sector,  Molina  shares were down 27% in premarket trading Friday after the company reported its fourth-quarter earnings late Thursday.  Molina posted a loss of $2.75 per share on revenue of $11.4 billion.
